{{refimprove|date=November 2014}}
'''Jupiter Cantab Limited''' was a [[Cambridge]] based [[home computer]] company. Its main product was the 1983 [[Forth (programming language)|Forth]] based [[Jupiter Ace]].
The company was founded in 1982 by two ex-[[Sinclair Research]] staffers, [[Richard Altwasser]] and [[Steve Vickers (academia)|Steven Vickers]]. Their machine was, externally, remarkably similar to the [[ZX Spectrum]], with a copycat rubber keyboard. It also used the same [[Zilog Z80|Z80]] processor. The Ace's video output was limited to monochrome like the [[ZX-81]].
The £90 Ace was a flop in both the UK and US markets: the Forth language, although considered powerful, was not as popular or accessible as the already well-established BASIC language featured in competing microcomputers. In the US it was sold as the ''Ace 4000''.
The company went bankrupt in November 1983 and its assets were sold to [[Boldfield Computing|Boldfield Computing Ltd]] in 1984. The remaining hardware was sold-off into 1985. Boldfield Computing Ltd also commissioned some software for it, including various games, database, and spread sheet software. Documentation to this exists and is held by the current owners of the brand.
The sale of Boldfield’s IT solution business in 2006, excluded the rights to the Jupiter Ace IP and brand, but this was later sold to [[Paul Andrews (producer)|Andrews UK Limited]] in 2015.{{cn|date=November 2018}}
